{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518290"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12906"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12906"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.03,0.81,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56043"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"2055"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44730"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of gradually worsening dyspnoea on exertion and non-productive cough. He has no weight loss or fever. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is an active smoker with a 30-pack year history, drinks two standard drinks of alcohol daily, and is a retired ship maker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has fine bibasal inspiratory crepitations on chest auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray demonstrates linear reticular opacities in both lower lobes of the lungs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary function tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFEV1: 65% (\u226580%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFVC: 70% (\u226580%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFEV1/FVC: 94% (\u226570%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETLC: 60% (\u226580%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDLCO: 68% (\u226580%)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchoscopy with bronchial alveolar lavage","No further investigations required","Transbronchial biopsy","High-resolution CT chest","Serum aspergillus precipitins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of asbestosis, including significant occupational exposure, gradually progressive dyspnoea, dry cough, and bibasal crepitations. Asbestosis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis a type of pneumoconiosis that is commonly seen in workers with exposure to asbestos, particularly shipbuilders, plumbers, welders, construction workers, and textile workers. Secondhand exposure to asbestos may also occur among family members of exposed workers.  The clinical evaluation of asbestosis is based on history, particularly occupational exposure to asbestos and physical examinations. The restrictive pattern on spirometry (reduced FVC with preserved FEV1/FVC ratio) and reduced DLCO further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations for asbestosis include chest X-ray or chest CT scan to look for radiographic presentations of asbestosis which are linear reticular opacities usually in the lower lobes of the lungs bilaterally. Chest X-ray is a useful initial imaging modality to detect lung changes, and is useful in primary care centers. However, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) \u003C/strong\u003Ehas superior sensitivity than other techniques in the detection of lung parenchymal changes such as early pleural thickening, which may be interpreted as extrapleural fat pads on chest X-ray. HRCT is also superior in excluding conditions such as emphysema, vessel prominence, overlying pleural disease, and bronchiectasis, which may confound radiographic interpretation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with bronchial alveolar lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely required for diagnosis when there is a clear exposure history and typical clinical and radiological findings. It may be considered if the diagnosis is uncertain or to exclude other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigations\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as imaging confirmation and assessment of disease extent are essential for diagnosis and management planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransbronchial biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely necessary for diagnosing asbestosis when there is significant exposure history and typical clinical and radiological findings. The risks of the procedure usually outweigh any diagnostic benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum aspergillus precipitins\u003C/strong\u003E testing would be appropriate if allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis was suspected, but the clinical presentation and occupational history strongly point towards asbestosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-Resolution Computed Tomography (HRCT) is the most sensitive imaging modality for detecting early parenchymal and pleural changes in asbestosis","Restrictive pattern on spirometry with reduced DLCO is characteristic of asbestosis","Occupational history and gradual onset of symptoms are key diagnostic features of asbestosis"],"references":["Bhandari J, Thada PK, Sedhai YR. Asbestosis. [Updated 2022 Sep 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555985/","THEM D. Diagnosis and initial management of nonmalignant diseases related to asbestos. American journal of respiratory and critical care medicine [Internet]. 2004;170:691-715. Available from: https://www.atsjournals.org/doi/full/10.1164/rccm.200310-1436ST?role=tab DOI: https://doi.org/10.1164/rccm.200310-1436ST"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56043"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12906"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56043"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T21:42:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T21:42:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.